We borrow these and other words of devotion from this epoch: it would be well to remember that just as the prac— tice of our own religious habits pro- duces in us the frame of mind which makes us feel able to pray, so was the religious conscience of the Jew de— pendent upon knowing and observing legal formalities.

We know that in accord with this rising enthusiasm for the law, the priests of the early post-exiliati period had been moving to magnify their office and enhance the sacredness of the Temple services.
